  "lesson_id": "lesson_auxiliary_zu",
  "lesson_title": "The Logic of 'Not': Negation with the Auxiliary ず (zu)",
  "lesson_summary": "This lesson introduces the primary tool for negation in Classical Japanese. By attaching the auxiliary 'zu' to the Mizenkei (Unrealized Base) you learned in the previous lesson, you can flip the logical state of any action.",
  "grammar_point": "auxiliary_zu",
  "grammar_explanation": {
    "concept": "The auxiliary 'zu' (ず) functions like a logical NOT operator (!). It negates the verb it attaches to. Because negation deals with something that 'has not happened,' it must always attach to the Mizenkei (未然形), the 'Unrealized Base' we established in Lesson 4.1.",
    "formation": "Verb (Mizenkei Base) + ず (zu) / ぬ (nu)",
    "variations": [
      "ず (zu): The terminal form, used to end a sentence or a clause (like a semicolon).",
      "ぬ (nu): The attributive form (Rentaikei), used when the negated verb modifies a noun or precedes certain particles."
    ],
    "common_confusions": [
      "Do not confuse the negative 'nu' (ぬ) with the completion auxiliary 'nu' (which attaches to a different base). If it's on the Mizenkei, it's always 'NOT'."
    ]
  },
  "teaching_sequence": [
    {
      "type": "introduction",
      "content": "In the previous lesson, we identified the **Mizenkei (未然形)** as the 'Unrealized Base'—a version of the verb used for things that haven't occurred yet. Today, we apply the most common 'tag' to that base: the auxiliary **ず (zu)**. In programming terms, if the Mizenkei is the variable, 'zu' is the logical NOT operator that changes the boolean value from TRUE to FALSE."
    },
